title:
Cohen--Macaulay Complexes, Duality Groups, and the dualizing module of
  ${\rm{Out}}(F_N)$

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We explain how Cohen-Macaulay classifying spaces are ubiquitous among discrete groups that satisfy Bieri-Eckmann duality, and compare BieriEckmann duality to duality results for Cohen-Macaulay complexes. We use this comparison to give a description of the dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ in terms of the local cohomology cosheaf of the spine of Outer space.

## 1. InTRODUCTION

1.1. Duality groups. A group $G$ is a (Bieri-Eckmann) duality group of dimension $n$ if there exists a $G$-module $D$ called the dualizing module and a fundamental class $c \in H_{n}(G ; D)$ such that for every integer $k$ and $G$-module $A$ there is an isomorphism

$$
c \cap-: H^{k}(G ; A) \xrightarrow{\cong} H_{n-k}(G ; A \otimes D)
$$

induced by the cap product. This notion, introduced in a seminal paper of Bieri and Eckmann [BE73], is a group-theoretic generalization of Poincaré duality. Indeed, fundamental groups of closed, aspherical manifolds are duality groups, and in this case the dualizing module $D=\mathbb{Z}$ is isomorphic to the orientation module of the fundamental group. However, duality groups form a much broader family, and are particularly prominent in low-dimensional topology and geometric group theory. Arithmetic lattices, mapping class groups, and outer automorphism groups of free groups are all, up to finite-index, duality groups [BS73, Har86, BF00].

Suppose that $G$ acts freely and cocompactly on a contractible CW-complex $X$. Then the compactly supported cohomology $H_{c}^{*}(X, \mathbb{Z})$ of $X$ is isomorphic to $H^{*}(G, \mathbb{Z} G)$ (as a graded $G$-module). A theorem of Bieri and Eckmann states that $G$ is a duality group of dimension $n$ if and only if $H_{c}^{*}(X, \mathbb{Z}) \cong H^{*}(G, \mathbb{Z} G)$ is torsionfree and concentrated in degree $*=n$ ([BE73, Theorem 4.5]). Furthermore, in the above situation the dualizing module satisfies $D \cong H_{c}^{n}(X, \mathbb{Z}) \cong H^{n}(G ; \mathbb{Z} G)$. As compactly supported cohomology is only invariant up to proper homotopy, it is desirable to work with compact classifying spaces (equivalently, cocompact EGs) when studying duality groups.
1.1.1. Duality of the mapping class group via Lefschetz duality. For $\mathrm{GL}(N, \mathbb{Z})$ and mapping class groups, the dualizing module can be described in terms of the homology of a particularly nice $G$-complex. For $\mathrm{GL}(N, \mathbb{Z})$ this $G$-complex is the rational Tits building [BS73], whereas for mapping class groups the dualizing module is isomorphic to the the homology of the curve complex $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$ [Har86]. Via Bieri-Eckmann duality, such concrete descriptions of dualizing modules have enabled a wealth of cohomological calculations [CFP12, CP17, CFP19, MPP21, PS22, BMP $^{+}$24, BPS23].

One goal of this article is to explain why we should not expect such a clean description for $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$, so for context we will take a short detour to sketch Harer's proof [Har86] that the dualizing module $D \cong H_{*}(\mathcal{C}(\Sigma))$ when $G=\operatorname{MCG}(\Sigma)$ (see also [Bro12, Iva87]). In short, the proof combines Lefschetz duality with a good understanding of the topology of $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$.

To give more details, let $\Sigma$ be a closed, orientable surface of genus $g \geq 2$. Its Teichmüller space $\mathcal{T}$ is homeomorphic to an open ball of dimension $6 g-6$. This is not cocompact under the action of $\operatorname{MCG}(\Sigma)$. However, one can pass to the thick part $X \subset \mathcal{T}$ formed by cutting out all thin regions $T_{c}$ consisting of marked surfaces where a simple closed curve $c$ is of length $<\epsilon$. These regions are contractible, and if $\epsilon$ is chosen small enough, regions overlap if and only if their defining curves are disjoint. One can use this to show that $X$ is a contractible manifold with boundary $\partial X \simeq \mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$. Harer proves that $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$ is homotopy equivalent to a wedge of spheres of dimension $2 g-2$, which allows him to apply Lefschetz duality to see that $H_{c}^{*}(X ; \mathbb{Z}) \cong H_{6 g-6 \rightarrow}(X, \partial X ; \mathbb{Z}) \cong H_{6 g-7 \rightarrow}(\partial X ; \mathbb{Z})$ is a torsion-free group concentrated in $*=4 g-5$. This gives an elegant description of the dualizing module of $\operatorname{MCG}(\Sigma)$ in terms of the homology of the curve complex.
1.1.2. The failure of Harer's approach for $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$. It is at this point one begins to see the difficulty in proving analogous results for outer automorphism groups of free groups. The analogous object to $\mathcal{T}$, which is Culler-Vogtmann's Outer space $\mathcal{C V}_{N}$, is not a manifold, so one does not have access to Lefschetz duality. Furthermore, although a common bordification of $\mathcal{C V}_{N}$ is at the heart of the duality proofs of both [BF00] and [BSV18], the homotopy type of its boundary is unknown (see [BG20] for a detailed discussion).

However, Vogtmann [Vog90] proved that Outer space does satisfy a strong local property called the Cohen-Macaulay (CM) property, which implies that even though $\mathcal{C V}_{N}$ does not satisfy Lefschetz duality, it does satisfy $C M$ duality. This is our second main topic of discussion.

# 1.2. Combinatorial (co)sheaves, the Cohen-Macaulay property, and CM 

duality. Let $X$ be a locally finite simplicial complex. We blur the destinction between $X$ and its associated poset of simplices, ordered by inclusion. A combinatorial sheaf $\mathcal{F}$ is a covariant functor from $X$ to the category of abelian groups. A combinatorial cosheaf $\mathcal{G}$ is a contravariant functor from $X$ to the category of abelian groups. In each of these cases, each simplex is assigned an abelian group, and there are compatible maps between these groups 'going up' (with respect to inclusion of simplices) in the case of a sheaf, and 'going down' in the case of a cosheaf. There is a natural way of taking (compactly supported) cohomology with coefficients in a combinatorial sheaf, and taking (locally finite) homology with coefficients in a combinatorial cosheaf. Importantly, taking local homology at simplices (in the classical sense) gives a combinatorial sheaf on $X$, and similarly local cohomology forms a combinatorial cosheaf.

A locally finite simplicial complex is a homology CM complex of dimension $n$ if the reduced homology $\bar{H}_{*}(X ; \mathbb{Z})$ is concentrated in degree $n$ and the local homology at each point is concentrated in degree $n$. If only the local condition holds, then $X$ is a local homology $C M$ complex. In this case, every maximal simplex will be of dimension $n$, and there is a fundamental class $[X] \in H_{n}^{0}\left(X ; h^{n}\right)$ that lives in

the top-dimensional locally finite homology with coefficients in the local cohomology cosheaf $h^{n}$ (this is described in Section 2). Poincaré duality for non-compact manifolds splits into two statements: one can either take compactly supported cohomology and regular homology, or instead use cohomology and locally finite (or Borel-Moore) homology. In the case of duality for locally CM spaces, a further split happens where one either takes twisted coefficients with the local homology sheaf $h_{n}$ on the left-hand side, or the local cohomology cosheaf on the right-hand side:

Theorem A (CM Duality, [WW23]). Let $X$ be a locally finite, n-dimensional, local homology CM complex. Then there are isomorphisms

$$
\begin{aligned}
H_{c}^{k}\left(X ; h_{n}\right) & \rightarrow H_{n-k}(X ; \mathbb{Z}) \\
H^{k}\left(X ; h_{n}\right) & \rightarrow H_{n-k}^{\mathrm{lf}}(X ; \mathbb{Z}) \\
H_{c}^{k}(X ; \mathbb{Z}) & \rightarrow H_{n-k}\left(X ; h^{n}\right) \\
H^{k}(X ; \mathbb{Z}) & \rightarrow H_{n-k}^{\mathrm{lf}}\left(X ; h^{n}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

induced by the cap product with the fundamental class $[X] \in H_{n}^{\mathrm{lf}}\left(X ; h^{n}\right)$.
The proof of Theorem A is given in [WW23], where we also discuss its relationship to related results, such as Verdier duality. For this introduction, we will limit ourselves to highlighting four salient features: the construction does not require working over a field, does not require passing to a derived category, is simplicial (hence amenable to explicit calculation), and is given by an explicit cap product.

There is a stronger, homotopical version of the CM condition, which will take a smaller role in this paper. ${ }^{1}$
1.3. New descriptions of dualizing modules. If $G$ is a duality group with a locally CM classifying space, CM duality can be applied to give alternative descriptions of dualizing modules. In [WW23], we show that the cap product in CM duality is equivariant with respect to the $G$-action, therefore:
Corollary B. If $G$ is a duality group of dimension $d$ and $G$ admits a free, cocompact action on a contractible, locally finite, homology $C M$ complex $X$ of dimension $n$, then the dualizing module is $G$-equivariantly isomorphic to $H_{n-d}\left(X ; h^{n}\right)$, where $h^{n}$ is the degree $n$ local cohomology cosheaf of $X$.

This gives a homological description of the dualizing module of $G$, at the cost of using more complicated coefficients. However, this alternative description may be more amenable to calculation.

If the space $X$ has the same dimension as $G$, then there is a further possible description of the dualizing module in terms of global section group $\Gamma(X)$ of the local homology sheaf. Let $\operatorname{Hom}_{c}(\Gamma(X), \mathbb{Z})$ be the group of compactly determined

Quillen's 1978 article [Qui78] was influential in introducing the CM condition to geometric topologists. In it, he used a homotopical condition on links, stating: 'we use the stronger definition so that our theorems are in their best form.' We say that the local homology sheaf on $X$ is semistable if the inverse system $\{\Gamma(K)\}_{K}$ of sections of the local homology sheaf over finite subcomplexes satisfies the Mittag-Leffler condition (see Section 2.6). Recall that while dualizing modules are always torsion-free, they are not necessarily free as abelian groups (see also Question 4).

Theorem C. Let $G, X$ be as in Corollary B. Furthermore suppose that $\operatorname{cd}(G)=$ $\operatorname{dim}(X)$. Then the local homology sheaf on $X$ is semistable if and only if the dualizing module $D$ of $G$ is free abelian. If this is the case then

$$
D \cong \operatorname{Hom}_{c}(\Gamma(X), \mathbb{Z})
$$

where $\Gamma(X)$ is the group of global sections of the local homology sheaf of $X$.
Corollary B and Theorem C show that the dualizing module in these situations can be read off from properties of both the local homology sheaf and the local cohomology cosheaf. The work surrounding Theorem C is influenced by, and uses parts of, Geoghegan's work on semistability in [Geo08, Chapters 12-13].
1.4. Outer space and $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$, Let $\mathcal{C V}_{N}$ and $\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}$ be Outer space and its reduced version (consisting of graphs with no separating edges). As we briefly mentioned earlier, there are two proofs that $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ is a duality group. Both either directly (in [BSV18]) or indirectly (in [BF00]) use the topology of a bordification of $\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}$ called Jewel space $\mathcal{J}_{N}$. This is a polyhedral complex sitting inside $\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}$ whose interior is homeomorphic to $\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}$.

Figure 1. The spine, Jewel space, Outer space, and its simplicial completion are all contractible. $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ acts properly and cococompactly on $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ and $\mathcal{J}_{N}$, but does not act cocompactly on $\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}$ and does not act properly on $\mathcal{F S}_{N}^{r}$. The boundary of Jewel space is homotopy equivalent to $\partial \mathcal{F} \mathcal{S}_{N}^{r}$, although this homotopy equivalence is also not proper; $\partial \mathcal{J}_{N}$ is locally finite, whereas $\partial \mathcal{F} \mathcal{S}_{N}^{r}$ is not.

Bux-Smillie-Vogtmann [BSV18] showed that $\mathcal{J}_{N}$ is homeomorphic to the bordification of Outer space used by Bestvina-Feighn in [BF00]. Vogtmann [Vog24] showed that $\partial \mathcal{J}_{N}$ is homotopy equivalent to the boundary of the simplicial completion of reduced Outer space, denoted by $\partial \mathcal{F} \mathcal{S}_{N}^{r}$ (equivalently, this space is the boundary of the free splitting complex). Jewel space can be seen as a thickening of the reduced spine $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} \subset \mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}$. Importantly, unlike the action on $\mathcal{C V}_{N}$, the action of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ on both $\mathcal{J}_{N}$ and $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ is cocompact.

In analogy with the mapping class group picture, $\partial \mathcal{J}_{N}$ plays a similar role to the curve complex, and it is natural to ask about the relationship between the dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ and the homology of $\partial \mathcal{J}_{N}$.

Theorem D. Let $\mathcal{X}_{N}$ be the spine of Outer space and let $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ be the spine of reduced Outer space. The dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ is isomorphic to the groups

$$
\begin{aligned}
& H_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}, h^{2 N-3}\right) \cong H_{c}^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}, \mathbb{Z}\right), \text { and } \\
& H_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}, h_{r}^{2 N-3}\right) \cong H_{c}^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}, \mathbb{Z}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $h^{2 N-3}$ and $h_{r}^{2 N-3}$ are the degree $2 N-3$ local cohomology cosheaves of $\mathcal{X}_{N}$ and $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$, respectively. In contrast, the homology of the simplicial boundary of (reduced) Outer space satisfies

$$
\begin{aligned}
& H_{3 N-5-k}\left(\partial \mathcal{F} \mathcal{S}_{N} ; \mathbb{Z}\right) \cong H_{c}^{k}\left(\left.\mathcal{X}_{N} ; h_{*}\left(\mathcal{C V}_{N}\right)\right|_{\mathcal{X}_{N}}\right), \text { and } \\
& H_{3 N-5-k}\left(\partial \mathcal{F} \mathcal{S}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right) \cong H_{c}^{k}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N} ; h_{*}\left(\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}\right)_{\mid \mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $h^{*}\left(\left.\mathcal{C V}_{N}\right)\right|_{\mathcal{X}_{N}}$ and and $h^{*}\left(\left.\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}\right)\right|_{\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}}$ are the restrictions of the local homology sheaf of Outer space (and reduced Outer space) to the spine (and its reduced version, respectively).

Given that $\partial \mathcal{J}_{N} \simeq \partial \mathcal{F} \mathcal{S}_{N}^{r}$ [Vog24, Proposition 2.14], this theorem shows that the difference between the homology of $\partial \mathcal{J}_{N}$ and the dualizing module is the difference between taking compactly supported cohomology of $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ with coefficients in $h_{*}\left(\left.\mathcal{C V}_{N}^{r}\right)\right|_{\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}}$ and $\mathbb{Z}$. Unfortunately there is no simple 'universal coefficient theorem' in this setting: such a result would be desirable as it would allow us to make this relationship between the homology of $\partial \mathcal{J}_{N}$ and the dualizing module precise. Theorem D also provides a homological description of the dualizing module, at the additional cost of using coefficients in the local cohomology cosheaf.

Using Vogtmann's proof that the (reduced) spine is homotopy CM, in Theorem 3.14 we show that a natural thickening of the (reduced) spine is homotopy CM. Using work of Brück-Gupta [BG20], we then show that the boundary of the thickened spine is homotopy equivalent to the boundary of the free splitting complex. With these results in hand, Theorem D is a consequence of CM duality. The first part follows from the fact that the spine is locally CM [Vog90] and the third isomorphism in Theorem A. The second part follows from a relative version of CM duality.
1.5. A bound for the top-dimensional cohomology of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$. Bieri-Eckmann duality allows one to translate problems from high-dimensional cohomology to lowdimensional homology, at the cost of understanding the dualizing module. If $G$ is the mapping class group or $\mathrm{GL}(n, \mathbb{Z})$ and $d$ is the virtual cohomological dimension of $G$, then $H^{d}(G ; \mathbb{Q})=0$. This is a result of Church-Farb-Putman [CFP12] in the case of the mapping class group, and Lee and Szczarba in the case of GL $(n, \mathbb{Z})$ [LS76], and is obtained by a vanishing result for the coinvariants of the associated dualizing module. In the case of $G=\mathrm{GL}(n, \mathbb{Z})$, the rational cohomology of $G$ also vanishes in codimensions one and two [CP17, BMP ${ }^{+} 24]$. The analogous codimension-one vanishing result was shown not to hold in the mapping class group in work of Chan-Galatius-Payne [CGP21].

Infamously, one cannot prove any such vanishing result for $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ : the vcd of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{7}\right)$ is 11 and Bartholdi [Bar16] showed that $H^{11}\left(\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{7}\right) ; \mathbb{Q}\right) \cong \mathbb{Q}$. The proof is computer-based, and it is not clear if there is a geometric origin for this cohomology class. While we cannot solve this problem, the methods in this paper allow us to obtain a resolution of the dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ via the chain

complex for $H_{*}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}, h_{r}^{2 N-3}\right)$. We describe this in Section 4, and use it to prove the following:

Theorem E. Let $\rho \in \mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ be a rose in the spine of reduced outer space, and let $\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)<\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ be the stabilizer of this rose. Then

$$
\operatorname{dim}\left(H^{2 N-3}\left(\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right) ; \mathbb{Q}\right)\right) \leq \operatorname{dim}\left(\left(h^{2 N-3}(\rho) \otimes \mathbb{Q}\right)_{\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)}\right)
$$

where $h^{2 N-3}(\rho)$ is the local cohomology of the reduced spine at this rose.
A detailed investigation of $h^{2 N-3}(\rho)$ as a $\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)$-representation is a topic for future research.
1.6. The CM condition does not imply Bieri-Eckmann duality. Out $\left(F_{N}\right)$ is not the only example of a duality group with a CM classifying space: in fact, CM complexes are ubiquitous among classifying spaces of duality groups. For instance, arithmetic groups and mapping class groups of surfaces are fundamental groups of orbifolds, and Brady and Meier proved that a right-angled Artin group (RAAG) is a duality group if and only if its associated Salvetti complex is a local homology CM complex [BM01, Theorem C and Lemma 5.1]. From this, one might hope that every fundamental group of a finite, closed (i.e. no free faces), aspherical, local homology CM complex is a duality group. However, we will see that this is not the case.
1.6.1. An example of Atanasov. One does not need to leave the world of RAAGs to find an aspherical CM complex $Y$ such that $\pi_{1}(Y)$ is not a duality group. Atanasov [Ata14] studied the two dimensional situation, and found an aspherical local-homotopy-CM complex (see Figure 2) with fundamental group $\mathbb{Z}^{2} * \mathbb{Z}^{2}$ which is not a duality group.

Using a version of CM duality, Atanasov [Ata14] gave sufficient conditions for fundamental groups of acyclic 2-complexes to be duality groups, although they require the singular parts of the 2-complex to be quite well-behaved (for instance a generic one relator group is a 2-dimensional duality group, but its presentation complex is not covered by Atanasov's criterion).

Figure 2. The group $G=\mathbb{Z}^{2} * \mathbb{Z}^{2}$ is not a duality group but is the fundamental group of an aspherical local homotopy CM complex $Y$ which has no free faces. The space $Y$ is given by gluing two tori $T_{1,1}$ each with one boundary to a disc.

1.6.2. The CM property and visible irreducibility. Atanasov's complex $Y$ given in Figure 2 satisfies slightly stronger conditions than having no free faces: the complex is visibly irreducible in the sense of Louder-Wilton (cf. [Wil24, Section 4], or Section 5 below). This is a condition for a complex to have no 'obvious' simplifications, and plays a key role in Louder-Wilton's proof that that one-relator groups with negative immersions are coherent [LW24]. In Theorem F, we show that visible irreduciblity can be described in terms of the local homology sheaf.

Theorem F. Let $Y$ be a 2-complex. The following are equivalent:

- $Y$ is visibly irreducible.
- $Y$ is a local homology CM complex and face maps of the local homology sheaf are surjective.
- $Y$ is a local homology CM complex and face maps of the local cohomology cosheaf are injective.

Theorem F, combined with Atanasov's example, shows that even with strong restrictions on the local homology sheaf, fundamental groups of aspherical CM complexes may not be duality groups.

# 1.7. Further Questions. 

Question 1. Does every duality group of finite type have a classifying space that is a local homology CM complex?

This fits in a series of questions going back to Wall [Wal79], who asked whether every Poincaré duality group admits a closed manifold as its classifying space. That question was answered in the negative by Davis [Dav98]: there are Poincaré duality groups of cohomological dimension $\geq 4$ that are not finitely presented. Davis [Dav00, Question 3.5] then asked if a finitely-presented, torsion-free group satisfies Poincaré duality over a ring $R$, does that group admit a closed $R$-homology manifold as its classifying space? This question has a negative answer when $R=\mathbb{Q}$ [Fow12], but is open for $R=\mathbb{Z}$. Note that a negative answer to this question would not imply a negative answer to Question 1.
Question 2. Suppose $Y$ is a finite, aspherical, local homology CM simplicial complex with fundamental group $G$. What conditions on the local homology sheaf of $Y$ (or alternatively, its universal cover $X=\tilde{Y}$ ) ensure that $G$ is a duality group?

Given the example in Figure 2, it is likely that global conditions on the universal cover are required, as one has to relate the local properties of the space to the behaviour of $H_{c}^{*}(X ; \mathbb{Z})$ : CAT( 0$)$ geometry was essential in Brady-Meier's classification of when RAAGs are duality groups, and discrete Morse theory was the local-to-global tool at the heart of both proofs that $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ is a duality group.

When $G$ is a duality group one can compare Bieri-Eckmann duality and CM duality via the isomorphisms

$$
H_{n-k}(G ; D) \stackrel{\varepsilon_{c}^{*} \cap-}{\cong} H^{k}(G ; \mathbb{Z}) \xrightarrow{\mid Y \mid \cap-} H_{n-k}\left(Y ; h_{Y}^{*}\right)
$$

Indeed, if $Y$ is CM then with a little work one can show that there exists a natural map

$$
\pi: H_{k}\left(G ; H_{c}^{*}(X ; \mathbb{Z})\right) \rightarrow H_{k}\left(Y ; h_{Y}^{*}\right)
$$

that is an isomorphism if and only if $G$ satisfies Bieri-Eckmann duality for the trivial module.

In light of Theorem C, one can as the following:
Question 3. Is the dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ free abelian? More generally, is the local homology sheaf on the spine of reduced Outer space semistable?

We suspect one might be able to obtain a positive answer to both of these questions via careful use of the proofs in [BF00] or [BSV18]. More generally, we include the following question of Peter Kropholler:

Question 4 (P. Kropholler). Is there an example of a Bieri-Eckmann duality group whose dualizing module is not free abelian?

By Exercise 4 of [Bro82, Chapter VII.10], when $D$ is free abelian we have $H_{k}(G ; M) \cong H^{n-k}(G ; \operatorname{Hom}(D, M))$ for all $M$ (i.e., one can also twist coefficients on the side of cohomology).
1.8. The structure of this article. In Section 2 we give an introduction to combinatorial sheaves and cosheaves and summarise the key results concerning CM duality. We describe how Corollary B and Theorem C follow from [WW23].

In Section 3 we introduce thickenings $\mathcal{L}_{N}$ and $\mathcal{K}_{N}$ of the spine and reduced spine of Outer space, show that they are homotopy CM, and use this to prove Theorem D.

In Section 5 we prove Theorem F on the relationship between the local homology sheaf and the visible irreducibility condition of Louder-Wilton.

# 2. Sheaf COHOMOLOGY and COSHEaf hOMOLOGY ON SIMPLICIAL COMPLEXES 

This section summarises the combinatorial sheaf theory needed for this paper; this is described in full in [WW23]. The main objects of interest to us in this paper are discrete groups (usually denoted $G$ ) and locally finite simplicial complexes (usually denoted $X$ ). We will also assume $X$ is oriented, so the vertices of each simplex have a preferred ordering. In particular there is a consistent notion of the front and back $k$-dimensional faces of simplices.
2.1. Combinatorial sheaves and cosheaves. The simplices of a complex form a poset with respect to inclusion, where $\sigma \leq \tau$ if $\sigma$ is contained in $\tau$. A combinatorial sheaf on $X$ is a functor $\mathcal{F}$ from the poset of simplicies to the category of abelian groups. In particular there is an abelian group $\mathcal{F}(\sigma)$ assigned to each simplex and a homomorphism

$$
\mathcal{F}(\sigma<\tau): \mathcal{F}(\sigma) \rightarrow \mathcal{F}(\tau)
$$

whenever $\sigma<\tau$. Requiring $\mathcal{F}$ to be a functor is equivalent to the condition that

$$
\mathcal{F}(\rho<\tau)=\mathcal{F}(\sigma<\tau) \circ \mathcal{F}(\rho<\sigma)
$$

whenever $\rho<\sigma<\tau$. A combinatorial cosheaf does the same thing except the maps go in the opposite direction; more precisely, a combinatorial cosheaf is a contravariant functor from the poset of simplices of $X$ to the category of abelian groups.

One can study sheaves and cosheaves on X valued in other categories, for instance $R$-modules. However in this paper, whenever we talk about a (co)sheaf, it will be valued in the category of abelian groups.
2.2. The local homology sheaf and the local cohomology cosheaf. Let $\hat{\text { st }}(\sigma)$ be the neighbourhood of $\sigma$ spanned by the interiors of the simplices $\tau \geq \sigma$ (including the interior of $\sigma$ itself). Then $X-\hat{\text { st }}(\sigma)$ is a subcomplex of $X$. Working over $\mathbb{Z}$, let $C_{\bullet}^{\sigma}(X)=C_{\bullet}(X, X-\hat{\text { st }}(\sigma))=C_{\bullet}(X) / C_{\bullet}(X-\hat{\text { st }}(\sigma))$ be the associated relative chain complex. The $k$ th local homology of $X$ at $\sigma$ is

$$
h_{k}(\sigma):=H_{k}\left(C_{\bullet}^{\sigma}(X)\right)
$$

As $C_{\bullet}^{\sigma}(X)$ is spanned by the simplices $\tau \geq \sigma$, this gives a simple combinatorial description of $h_{k}(\sigma)$.

If $\sigma \leq \tau$ then we can view $C_{\bullet}^{\tau}(X)$ as a quotient complex of $C_{\bullet}^{\sigma}(X)$, which induces a map

$$
h_{k}(\sigma<\tau): h_{k}(\sigma) \rightarrow h_{k}(\tau)
$$

induced by the associated map of pairs $(X, X-\hat{\text { st }}(\sigma)) \rightarrow(X, X-\hat{\text { st }}(\tau))$. Note that if $\sigma$ is maximal then

$$
C_{\bullet}^{\sigma}(X)=\langle\sigma\rangle
$$

and $h_{k}(\sigma)=\mathbb{Z}$ in the dimension of $\sigma$ and is trivial in every other degree.
We say that $X$ is a local homology $C M$ complex of dimension $n$ if $h_{k}(\sigma)=0$ unless $k=n$ for all $\sigma \in X$. This implies that every maximal simplex is $n$-dimensional, and as there are no $n+1$ simplices we have a simpler description

$$
h_{n}(\sigma)=\operatorname{ker}\left(C_{n}^{\sigma}(X) \rightarrow C_{n-1}^{\sigma}(X)\right)
$$

of the $n$th local homology. In particular, when $X$ is locally CM all the local homology groups are free abelian.

Taking $C_{\sigma}^{\bullet}(X)=\operatorname{Hom}\left(C_{\bullet}^{\sigma}(X), \mathbb{Z}\right)$ gives dual cochain complexes which compute local cohomology. This gives a (graded) cosheaf $h^{*}$ on $X$, with corestriction maps $h^{*}(\tau>\sigma): h^{*}(\tau) \rightarrow h^{*}(\sigma)$. Typically for us $X$ will be a local homology CM complex and we will only be interested in the degree $n$ parts $h_{n}$ and $h^{n}$.
2.3. Sheaf cohomology and cosheaf homology. Let $\mathcal{F}$ be a combinatorial sheaf on $X$ and let $X_{k}$ be the set of $k$-simplices of $X$. We define

$$
C^{k}(X ; \mathcal{F}):=\prod_{\sigma \in X_{k}} \mathcal{F}(\sigma)
$$

Let $|\sigma: \tau|=(-1)^{i}$ if $\sigma$ is the $i$ th facet of $\tau$, and set $|\sigma: \tau|=0$ otherwise. If $\alpha \in \mathcal{F}(\sigma)$ and $\sigma \in X_{k}$, we define a coboundary map termwise on $C^{\bullet}(X ; \mathcal{F})$ by

$$
\delta \alpha=\sum_{\tau \in X_{k+1}}|\sigma: \tau| \mathcal{F}(\sigma<\tau)(\alpha)
$$

One can verify that this gives a cochain complex whose cohomology we define to be the cohomology of $X$ with coefficients in $\mathcal{F}$. When $X$ is locally finite, there is a compactly supported version of this where

$$
C_{c}^{k}(X ; \mathcal{F}):=\bigoplus_{\sigma \in X_{k}} \mathcal{F}(\sigma)
$$

with the coboundary maps defined the same way.

Similarly, the cosheaf homology of a cosheaf $\mathcal{G}$ is the homology of the chain complex given by

$$
C_{k}(X ; \mathcal{G}):=\bigoplus_{\sigma \in X_{k}} \mathcal{G}(\sigma)
$$

and a boundary operator defined by

$$
\partial \alpha=\sum_{i=0}^{k}(-1)^{i} \mathcal{G}\left(\sigma>\sigma_{i}\right)(\alpha)
$$

for $\alpha \in \mathcal{G}(\sigma)$ and $\sigma \in X_{k}$, with $\sigma_{i}$ denoting the $i$ th face of $\sigma$. When $X$ is locally finite, we can also define locally finite homology with coefficients in $\mathcal{G}$ by taking homology of the chain complex with terms

$$
C_{k}^{\mathrm{lf}}(X ; \mathcal{G}):=\prod_{\sigma \in X_{k}} \mathcal{G}(\sigma)
$$

and the same boundary operator as above.
2.4. Cap products and the fundamental class. Suppose that $X$ is $n$-dimensional and locally finite. Then $h^{n}(\sigma)=\left\langle\sigma^{*}\right\rangle$ for every $n$-simplex $\sigma$, and the formal sum

$$
[X]:=\sum_{\sigma \in X_{n}} \sigma^{*}
$$

determines an element of $H_{n}^{\mathrm{lf}}\left(X, h^{n}\right)$ called the fundamental class [WW23, Section 4.2.1]. If $X$ is connected and locally CM, then $H_{n}^{\mathrm{lf}}\left(X, h^{n}\right)=\mathbb{Z}$ and is generated by the fundamental class. In [WW23], we give formulations of the cap product required for all permutations of coefficients given in Theorem A, however in this paper we will only give the cap product

$$
H_{k}^{\mathrm{lf}}\left(X, h^{n}\right) \otimes H_{c}^{\mathrm{f}}(X, \mathbb{Z}) \xrightarrow{\cap} H_{k-l}\left(X, h^{n}\right)
$$

induced by the map

$$
\eta \cap \psi=\sum_{\sigma \in X_{k}} \psi\left(\sigma_{\mathbb{Z} k-l}\right) h^{n}\left(\sigma>\sigma_{\leq k-l}\right)\left(\eta_{\sigma}\right)
$$

where $\eta \in C_{k}^{\mathrm{lf}}\left(X, h^{n}\right), \psi \in C_{c}^{\mathrm{f}}(X, \mathbb{Z})$, and $\eta_{\sigma} \in h^{n}(\sigma)$ is the value of $\eta$ at $\sigma$. If $\sigma=$ $\left[v_{0}, \ldots, v_{k}\right]$ then $\sigma_{\geq k-l}=\left[v_{k-l}, \ldots, v_{k}\right]$ is the back $l$-face and $\sigma_{\leq k-l}=\left[v_{0}, \ldots, v_{k-l}\right]$ is the front $(k-l)$-face of $\sigma$.

When $\eta=[X]$ is the fundamental class, $\eta_{\sigma}=\sigma^{*}$ for every $n$-simplex $\sigma$ and (2) can be unpacked further (see [WW23, Section 4.2.2] for details).
2.5. Relative versions of CM duality. Let $X$ be a locally finite simplicial complex and $L$ be a full subcomplex of $X$, and let $L^{\mathrm{vc}}$ be the full complex spanned by vertices in $X-L$ (we call $L^{\text {vc }}$ the vertex complement of $L$ ). The cap product defined in the above setting applies for pairs $(X, L)$, as long as in any simplex $\sigma$, the orientation of $X$ orders vertices in $L$ before those in $L^{\text {vc }}$. This is so that back faces, when it is appropriate, lie in $L^{\text {vc }}$ (see [WW23, Section 2.5.4] for details).

Theorem 2.1 (Relative CM Duality). Let $X$ be locally finite homology CM complex of dimension $n$ with local homology sheaf $h_{*}$ and local cohomology sheaf $h^{*}$. Let $L$ be

a full subcomplex of $X$ and orient $L^{\mathrm{vc}}$ before $L$. Then capping with the fundamental induces isomorphisms

$$
\begin{aligned}
& H_{c}^{I}\left(L ; h_{n} \mid{ }_{L}\right) \xrightarrow{|\bar{X}|^{c_{n}}} H_{n-l}\left(X, L^{\mathrm{vc}} ; \mathbb{Z}\right), \text { and } \\
& H_{c}^{I}(X, L ; \mathbb{Z}) \xrightarrow{|\bar{X}|^{c_{n}}} H_{n-l}\left(L^{\mathrm{vc}} ; h^{n} \left.\right|_{L^{\mathrm{vc}}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

There are other versions of these isomorphisms given in Theorem 4.26 of [WW23]; we only give two relevant ones here.
2.6. Semistability and the global section group. The subcomplexes of $X$ form a direct system with respect to inclusion. If $K$ is a subcomplex, we use

$$
\Gamma(K)=H^{0}\left(K ; h_{*} \mid K\right)
$$

to denote the group of sections of the local homology sheaf of $X$ over $K$. If $K \subset L$, then restriction of sections gives a restriction homomorphism $r_{L K}: \Gamma(L) \rightarrow \Gamma(K)$. Local finiteness of $X$ implies that we can restrict our attention to sections over finite subcomplexes: these form an inverse system whose limit is still the global section group $\Gamma(X)$.

An inverse system $\left\{A_{i}\right\}$ with maps $\left\{f_{i j}: A_{i} \rightarrow A_{j}\right\}$ indexed by a filtered poset $I$ is semistable if for all $i \in I$ there exists $j \geq i$ such that for all $k \geq j \geq i$ the map $f_{k i}$ has the same image in $A_{i}$ independently of $k$. This is also known as the Mittag-Leffler condition.

Definition 2.2 (Semistability of the local homology sheaf). We say that the local homology sheaf on $X$ is semistable if the inverse system of sections of $h_{*}$ over finite subcomplexes is semistable.

If $A$ is an abelian group, we say a homomorphism $f: \Gamma(X) \rightarrow A$ is compactly determined if there exists a finite subcomplex $K \subset X$ such that $f(s)=0$ whenever a section $s \in \Gamma(X)$ vanishes on $K$ (this implies the image of a section under $f$ is determined by its restriction to $K$ ). We use $\operatorname{Hom}_{c}(\Gamma(X), A)$ to denote the group of compactly determined homomorphisms from $\Gamma(X)$ to $A$. Using work of Geoghegan [Geo08], in [WW23] we prove the following:
Theorem 2.3 ([WW23], Corollary 3.19). Suppose that $X$ is locally CM. Then the local homology sheaf on $X$ is semistable if and only if $H_{0}\left(X ; h^{*}\right)$ is a free abelian group. If this is the case, then

$$
H_{0}\left(X ; h^{*}\right) \cong \operatorname{Hom}_{c}(\Gamma(X), \mathbb{Z})
$$

This allows us to prove Theorem C from the introduction.
Theorem 2.4 (Theorem C). Let $G$ be a duality group that admits a free, cocompact action on a contractible, locally finite, homology CM complex $X$ of dimension equal to $\operatorname{cd}(G)$. Then the local homology sheaf on $X$ is semistable if and only if the dualizing module $D$ of $G$ is free abelian. If this is the case then

$$
D \cong \operatorname{Hom}_{c}(\Gamma(X), \mathbb{Z})
$$

where $\Gamma(X)$ is the group of global sections of the local homology sheaf of $X$.
Proof. When the dimension of $X$ is the same as the cohomological dimension of $G$, under the above hypothesis we have $D \cong H_{0}\left(X ; h^{*}\right)$ by CM duality (Theorem A).

# 4. BOUNDING THE TOP-DIMENSIONAL COHOMOLOGY OF $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ 

In this section, we see how cosheaf homology gives a resolution for the dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$, and use this to prove the following:

Theorem 4.1. Let $\rho \in \mathcal{X}_{N}^{c}$ be a rose in the spine of reduced outer space, and let $\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)<\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ be the stabilizer of this rose. Then

$$
\operatorname{dim}\left(H^{2 N-3}\left(\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right) ; \mathbb{Q}\right)\right) \leq \operatorname{dim}\left(\left(h^{2 N-3}(\rho) \otimes \mathbb{Q}\right)_{\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)}\right)
$$

where $h^{2 N-3}(\rho)$ is the local cohomology of the reduced spine at this rose.
Recall that a rose is a point $T$ in the spine such that $T / F_{N}$ is a graph with one vertex and $N$ loops, and we use $M_{G}$ to denote the group of coinvariants of a $G$-module $M$. As $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ is a virtual duality group, it is a duality group of dimension $2 N-3$ over $\mathbb{Q}$ [Bie81, Theorem 9.9]. In particular this implies:

$$
H^{2 N-3}\left(\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right) ; \mathbb{Q}\right) \cong H_{0}\left(\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right) ; D \otimes \mathbb{Q}\right)=(D \otimes \mathbb{Q})_{\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)}
$$

where $D$ is the dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$. To prove Theorem 4.1, we will show that with integer coefficients one has

$$
D_{\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)} \subseteq h^{2 N-3}(\rho)_{\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)}
$$

which implies the dimensional inequality after passing to rational coefficients. As above, the dualizing module of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ is

$$
D=H_{c}^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{c} ; \mathbb{Z}\right)
$$

As we are in the top dimension, the coboundary map is trivial so $H_{c}^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right)$ is generated by cohomology classes of the form $\left[\alpha^{*}\right]$, as $\alpha$ varies over the topdimensional simplices of $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$. Viewing $G=\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ as acting on $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ on the left, this gives $H_{c}^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right)$ the usual right $G$-module structure by

$$
\left[\alpha^{*}\right] g=\left[g^{-1}(\alpha)^{*}\right]
$$

By [Vog90], the spine is locally Cohen-Macaulay, so we can apply CM duality (Theorem 2.1) to obtain an isomorphism

$$
\left[\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}\right] \cap-: H_{c}^{k}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right) \stackrel{\cong}{\rightrightarrows} H_{2 N-3-k}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)
$$

where $h^{2 N-3}$ is the local cohomology cosheaf of the spine and $\left[\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}\right] \in H_{2 N-3}^{\text {If }}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$ is the fundamental class. As $H_{c}^{*}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right)$ is concentrated in degree $2 N-3, H_{*}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$ is concentrated in degree zero, so its chain complex is acyclic. This gives a resolution

$$
\cdots \rightarrow C_{1}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right) \rightarrow C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right) \rightarrow D \rightarrow 0
$$

of the dualizing module. The modules in this chain complex are (see Equation (1))

$$
C_{k}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)=\oplus_{\sigma \in\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}\right)_{k}} h^{2 N-3}(\sigma)
$$

where $h^{2 N-3}(\sigma)=H^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}, \mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}-\operatorname{st}(\sigma)\right)$ is the local homology at $\sigma$. To distinguish where local homology classes live, for $\phi \in h^{2 N-3}(\sigma)$ we use $\sigma \triangleleft \phi$ to denote the corresponding element of $C_{n}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$ in the $h^{2 N-3}(\sigma)$-summand.

At the chain level, the cap product with the fundamental class $\left[\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}\right]$ given in [WW23] is the $G$-equivariant (see [WW23, Section 5]) map

$$
c_{2 N-3}: C^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right) \rightarrow C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)
$$

given by

$$
c_{2 N-3}\left(\alpha^{*}\right)=\alpha_{0} \triangleleft\left[\alpha^{*}\right]
$$

where $\alpha_{0}$ is the first vertex of $\alpha$ (using the ordering/orientation on $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ induced by the poset structure), and $\alpha_{0} \triangleleft\left[\alpha^{*}\right]$ lives in the local cohomology at the vertex $\alpha_{0}$. The quickest way to see this is via Equation (14) on page 13 of [WW23], noting that the fundamental class $\left[\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}\right]$ is represented by the infinite sum $\sum \alpha \triangleleft\left[\alpha^{*}\right]$, as $\alpha$ ranges over all maximal simplices. In the poset structure we use on the spine every maximal simplex $\alpha$ is given by a chain

$$
T_{0}<T_{1}<\cdots<T_{2 N-3}
$$

where the initial vertex $T_{0}$ of $\alpha$ is a rose. We can leverage this to restrict the image of $c_{2 N-3}$ :

Proposition 4.2. Let $R$ be the submodule of $C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$ spanned by the local cohomology groups of the roses in $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$. Every element of $D=C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right) / \operatorname{im} d_{1}$ has a representative in $R$.

Proof. The cap product $c_{2 N-3}$ induces an isomorphism between $H_{c}^{2 N-3}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; \mathbb{Z}\right)$ and $H_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$. The image of $c_{2 N-3}$ is contained in $R$ by (9), as the first vertex $\alpha_{0}$ of any maximal simplex $\alpha$ is a rose. In particular, $H_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$ is generated by the classes in $R$.

Corollary 4.3. Let $R$ be the submodule of $C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$ spanned by the local cohomology groups of the roses in $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$, and let

$$
d_{1}: C_{1}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right) \rightarrow C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)
$$

be the boundary map in cosheaf homology. Then

$$
D \cong R /\left(\operatorname{im} d_{1} \cap R\right)
$$

Proof. By CM dualiy,

$$
D \cong H_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right) \cong C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right) / \operatorname{im} d_{1}
$$

and the inclusion $R \subset C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right)$ induces an injection

$$
R /\left(\operatorname{im} d_{1} \cap R\right) \hookrightarrow C_{0}\left(\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r} ; h^{2 N-3}\right) / \operatorname{im} d_{1} \cong D
$$

By Proposition 4.2, every element of $D$ has a representative in $R$, so this map is also surjective.

Proposition 4.4. Let $R$ be as above and let $I$ be the augmentation ideal of the group ring of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$. If $\rho$ is a rose in $\mathcal{X}_{N}^{r}$ and $\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)$ is its stabilizer in $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ then

$$
R / R I=R_{\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)} \cong h^{2 N-3}(\rho)_{\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)}
$$

Proof. As $R$ decomposes as a direct summand over the $h^{2 N-3}(\rho)$ and $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ acts transitively on the summands, it follows that

$$
R=\operatorname{Ind}_{\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)}^{\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)} h^{2 N-3}(\rho)
$$

i.e. $R$ is the induced representation of the $\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)$ representation $h^{2 N-3}(\rho)$ (see e.g. Proposition III.5.3 in [Bro82]). Then

$$
H_{*}\left(\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right) ; R\right) \cong H_{*}\left(\operatorname{Stab}(\rho) ; h^{2 N-3}(\rho)\right)
$$

by Shapiro's lemma [Bro82, Proposition III.6.2]. The result follows by taking $*=$ 0 .

Proof of Theorem 4.1. By Corollary 4.3, we have

$$
D \cong \frac{R}{\operatorname{im} d_{1} \cap R}
$$

therefore the coinvariants of this module are given by

$$
D_{\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)} \cong \frac{R}{\operatorname{im} d_{1} \cap R+R I} \subset \frac{R}{R I} \cong h^{2 N-3}(\rho)_{\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)}
$$

Theorem 4.1 is then a consequence of $\operatorname{Out}\left(F_{N}\right)$ being a duality group over $\mathbb{Q}$ with rational dualizing module $D \otimes \mathbb{Q}$.

Remark 4.5. We finish this section with some remarks.

- To show that the inclusion from Equation (7) is actually an isomorphism, it follows from the proof that it is enough to show that $R I$ contains $\operatorname{im} d_{1} \cap R$. This is definitely false in the unreduced case, and seems unlikely to be true even in the reduced setting.
- The representation theory of the $\operatorname{Stab}(\rho)$ action on the cohomology of the link (or equivalently, the local cohomology) is well understood in terms of tree representations of the symmetric group. See [Bar90] and [RW96]. For instance, in the unreduced setting the dimension of $h^{2 N-3}(\rho)$ is $(2 N-$ 2)! However, the structure of the link is much less well-understood in the reduced spine.

- While we suspect it may be possible to prove Theorem 4.1 without using CM duality, the theorem was only formulated after a careful consideration of the the resolution of the dualizing module obtained in Equation (8). Furthermore, we found that the cap product in CM duality facilitated a particularly clean proof of Proposition 4.2.

# 5. 2-COMPLEXES, VISIBLE IRREducIBILITY AND THE LOCAL HOMOLOGY SHEAF 

In dimension two, links of points are homeomorphic to graphs, and we will see that the local Cohen-Macaulay condition is equivalent to the graphs that appear as vertex links being connected and nondegenerate (not a single point). A related condition called visible irreducibility, appears in work of Louder and Wilton [LW24] (reformulated as below in [Wil24, Remark 4.2]). Informally this says that there are no obvious local simplifications one can perform on the 2-complex. More precisely, a complex is visibly irreducible if:
(i) every vertex link contains at least one edge;
(ii) every vertex link is connected;
(iii) vertex links do not contain leaves; and
(iv) vertex links do not have cut vertices.

Otherwise, a complex is visibly reducible. We now turn to Theorem F from the introduction, which is restated below.

Theorem 5.1. Let $Y$ be a simplicial 2-complex. Then $Y$ is a local homology $C M$ complex if and only if it satisfies (i) and (ii). Furthermore, the following are equivalent:

- $Y$ is visibly irreducible.
- $Y$ is a local homology CM complex and the restriction maps of the local homology sheaf are surjective.
- $Y$ is a local homology CM complex and the corestriction maps of the local cohomology cosheaf are injective.

Proof. We first show that if $Y$ is locally CM then it satisfies (i) and (ii). If $Y$ is locally CM then it is pure (all of its maximal simplices are 2 -simplices), so in particular every vertex is contained in a 2 -simplex and (i) holds. To see that (ii) also holds, let $V \in Y$ be a vertex, and let $\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)$ be the vertex link. By comparing the chain complexes $C_{\bullet}^{V}(Y)$ (as defined in Section 2.2) and $\tilde{C}_{\bullet-1}\left(\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)\right)$ (that computes the reduced homology of the link) we see that $h_{k}(V) \cong \tilde{H}_{k-1}\left(\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)\right)$ : every adjacent edge $E$ at $V$ determines a vertex $v_{E} \in \operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)$ and 2 -simplices containing $V$ give edges in $\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)$. If (ii) does not hold, there exists a vertex $V$ such that $\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)$ is a disconnected graph, so that $h_{1}(V)=\tilde{H}_{0}\left(\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)\right)$ is nontrivial. So $Y$ being locally CM also implies (ii).

Now assume that $Y$ satisfies (i) and (ii). We want to to show that the local homology $h_{*}(\sigma)$ is concentrated in degree 2 for every simplex $\sigma \in Y$. We start with the vertices: by (i) and (ii) each vertex link is a non-empty connected graph with at least one edge, so $\tilde{H}_{*}\left(\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)\right)$ is concentrated in degree 1 , and therefore $h_{*}(V) \cong \tilde{H}_{*-1}\left(\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)\right)$ is concentrated in degree 2. Moving on to the edges, $h_{*}(E)$ is concentrated in degree two if and only if $E$ is contained in a face. If this is not the case, $E$ will be an isolated vertex in each of its vertex links, contradicting (ii) (as there is at least one edge in each vertex link by (i)). The local homology at each

2-simplex $\sigma$ satisfies $h_{2}(\sigma)=\mathbb{Z}$ and $h_{k}(\sigma)=0$ for $k \neq 2$ by maximality. Putting all of the above together, $Y$ is a local homology CM complex if and only if the vertex links of $Y$ satisfy (i) and (ii).

We now move on the equivalence of the bullet points. As there is no torsion in local (co)homology when the complex is locally CM, equivalence of the second and third bullet points follows from the universal coefficient theorem. Therefore we will focus on the local homology sheaf. Firstly, if $F$ is a 2 -simplex in $Y$ and $E$ is an edge of $F$, the map $h_{2}(E) \rightarrow h_{2}(F)$ is surjective if and only if the local homology $h_{2}(E)$ does not vanish. This happens if and only if $E$ is contained in at least two 2 -simplices. This in turn is equivalent to vertex links not containing leaves.

Now suppose that $Y$ satisfies (i), (ii) and (iii). As above let $V$ be a vertex of an edge $E \in Y$. The local homology in $Y$ at $E$ only considers 2 -simplices containing $E$, so in terms of the notation above we have

$$
h_{2}(E) \cong H_{1}\left(\Gamma, \Gamma-\operatorname{sh}_{\Gamma}\left(v_{E}\right)\right)
$$

where $\operatorname{sh}_{\Gamma}\left(v_{E}\right)$ is the open star of $v_{E}$ in the vertex link $\Gamma$. Furthermore, one can check that the map $h_{2}(V) \rightarrow h_{2}(E)$ is the same as the map

$$
H_{1}(\Gamma) \rightarrow H_{1}\left(\Gamma, \Gamma-\operatorname{sh}_{\Gamma}\left(v_{E}\right)\right)
$$

induced by the inclusion of pairs $(\Gamma, \emptyset) \rightarrow\left(\Gamma, \Gamma-\operatorname{sh}_{\Gamma}\left(v_{E}\right)\right)$. By considering the long exact sequence in homology, the cokernel of $h_{2}(E) \rightarrow h_{2}(V)$ is then isomorphic to

$$
\check{H}_{0}\left(\Gamma-\operatorname{sh}_{\Gamma}\left(v_{E}\right)\right)
$$

Hence the map $h_{2}(V) \rightarrow h_{2}(E)$ is surjective unless $\Gamma-\operatorname{sh}_{Y}\left(v_{E}\right)$ has more than one component, or equivalently unless $v_{E}$ is a cut vertex of $\operatorname{lk}_{Y}(V)=\Gamma$.

abstract:
We explain how Cohen--Macaulay classifying spaces are ubiquitous among
discrete groups that satisfy Bieri--Eckmann duality, and compare Bieri--Eckmann
duality to duality results for Cohen--Macaulay complexes. We use this
comparison to give a description of the dualizing module of ${\rm{Out}}(F_N)$
in terms of the local cohomology cosheaf of the spine of Outer space.
